As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced during the year alone of 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with photo and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election and withdraw citizens with a judicial file their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photo.
