The Higgs Boson Decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole emotion, last summer, and because.
It is believed that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, nothing but that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model – our best, or “less worse” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely sure that it is Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Additionally, new data revealed this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm it, but there is still a lack of data to be completely sure of it.
Let’s still assume that it’s well about Higgs, as the chances of getting wrong seem small, and let’s see what it’s about.
There is, in this low world, a fatally inevitable law wishing that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to violate this rule - and don't try too strong, you'll hurt yourself.
But even if the particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli’s principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quantum state” – that “state” consisting grosso modo in some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can actually be at the same place, at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, otherwise) The Particle Adventure, the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "power particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, we must emphasize here, are not all so exotic beasts as we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the “light particle” which is the “messenger” of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “interrupts” the electromagnetic field in that specific place, a bit like a stone thrown into a basin.
From this "interruption" is born an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the "power-bearing" bosons.
More stable fields
The same goes with the Higgs boson, to this difference close that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "interrupted" so that this boson appears.
But this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it was a frozen basin of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like that of the CERN – the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km circonference ring! – to reach such energies.
The analogue with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, it’s not all the particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do it have a mass, while others (such as the photon) do not have it.
Now, what can all these research bring, ask Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, it serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to examine any gap between the observations and predictions of the MS.
There are many people who desire to find them, because any difference could open a door to a "new physical" and kill some holes in the Model.
This, we must say, still has enormous shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oups!).
However, no such disagreements have been found in the CERN so far.
Impacts
The consequences of these research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-World, they are harder to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be.
Keep in mind: at the beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They interviewed scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we’ve already said fire the physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsated), in 1962 – in the beginning the laser was rather seen as a “laboratory gadget”.
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not his original intention at all, now serves as a "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and has won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that LHC’s activities will necessarily transform our lives, but that means that, really, we never know...
