She told me I was finished.
No all-powerful care
Dre Martel believes that 90% of the sick who ask to die thank the nurse for not accessing their request after they were relieved from their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Grand Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors then often resort to palliative sedation, which comes to sleeping the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
You can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
More and more, the unleashed patient will have the possibility of having this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” that means “I want to be relieved.”
