With Bitcoin, Pay and Sell Without Banks
All the opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing costs between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made of bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the way of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from pair to pair.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoin as a donation or a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a top of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2, five months later, before returning today around a dozen dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin distinguishes itself from other types of virtual currency such as the “credits”, used to advance in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, every time, a central authority controls and deals with the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all the network nodes are both account book depositors, verificators, currency emitters, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the way of an email.
Unless a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
The network can therefore verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file content, it is also possible to make sure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, broadcast throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched on the computers, and whose winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a file hashing phase, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "tak" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the set.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (a lot of zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructively linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because both have different footprints.
The computer that has solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred million, leaving the margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also highlighted with every increase in calculation power.
The life of the network has already had high and low.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The fault used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has this deficiency.
Weight players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that 80% of bitcoin is not circulating.
In November, “Gigant Soldiers” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement with traders, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to communicate an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who assures to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to be required, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to re-evaluate the various risks, now considered to be high, if this currency succeeds.
