At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee at the House of Representatives, you discussed a Czech-German project in which the legislation on public procurement of the two countries was compared.
What was it specifically?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, the European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and the specific national legislation, as well as a practice that is called followed by it.
We’ve gathered all this and although this control procedure is not yet completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be “more strict and better quality”, yet, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This therefore confirms that it is not sufficient to constantly develop more and more detailed rules but that it is necessary to dedicate itself to the implementation of the law itself.
What can this project actually help you and what is the result for you?
A common control of this type should just help us stop trying to clarify the laws, lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the matter at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering the market thresholds, this goal will not necessarily be achieved.
It could be that this system is so immersed by the paperasse that those looking for the faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal issues regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an organization similar to our ISC or a different way of organization?
As for institutions, the same as the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof works there which is organized similarly, it also has a council composed slightly differently, but these two institutions act fundamentally in a similar way.
The skills are also, to a certain extent, similar, with a nuance however in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, therefore it also has such accounts at the level of the different countries.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country corresponds to the state resources.
The public funds managed at us by the regions and municipalities, are there controlled at the level of the countries’ accounts.
Is it more simple than our legislation?
I’t want to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas, Germany is often referred to as a model but it can’t be said that it does better in all areas.
Could it be because they have better inspectors?
