Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern Block (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of agency projects.
However, the route from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld’s conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled “Introduction to Astronomy.”
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book Introduction to Astronautics.
Ledit Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Since 1925 a drainage was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the missile should be used to push or freeze the drainage.
The only information known about this drainage is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The preserved documents show that this research had reached the stage of the trials.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photovoltaic hunting missile, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
The two projects were aimed at the military use of missile engines.
Just before the war, all the projects of using the missile technique were conducted by the provisional scientific consultative committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work dedicated to aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a company in the November 1954 issue of the problem newspaper, which contains four more detailed articles dedicated to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company dedicated to astronomy.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronomical Society (PTA) deployed efforts to join the International Astronomical Federation (founded in 1951) and since autumn, the PTA became a regular member of it.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronaut Federation.
He kept his office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA contributed significantly to the successful development of the meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This 1800 meters wide missile had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Later a improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 missile flight tests began in the Bledov desert.
The missile had a length of 1.4 meters and was likely weighing 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should be able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 should have a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all the development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 was developed between 1962 and 1965, successed to the first RM-type missiles.
The missile, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A missile had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of engines was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 missiles were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The new versions were Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It should also be mentioned that Poland entered the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The abolition of the law on public utility works is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court abolished the law on public utility works.
This decision raised a strong discussion in the public.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberalism-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This concrete means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and of free (without limits) circulation of private capital allied to a narrow financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the labour price (wages) generate pressure on the prices.
It should be put under this term the following meaning: a producer strives through the import of low-selling goods to resist economic competition by “making” the competitor’s price, in order to remove a greater part of the market and thus increase his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, or buy at a low price, or disappear. The result is a significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since the private capital has no social responsibility and therefore responsibility toward the unemployment it generates, the social burden of the state necessarily increases.
All this situation intensifies the perfect bad will of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole society by this race to profit.
This situation is so popular that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The scrupulous practices of private capital generate in the different economies a situation in which governments of different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own population to the mercy of private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is mainly manifested in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the dictates of private capital prices, in the field of wages.
This occurs, on the one hand, by a system of economic restrictions in case of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, by the restriction of workers’ rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In RFA, there have been for years points of public distribution of food for the poor who cannot supply their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted by millions.
As part of the increased competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common that employees receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement so that they reach the vital minimum.
For example, such a scandal has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern member states of the EU generate, without a doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as it was in the nineteenth century), or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day the private capital will invest in their country.
Here we have to ask ourselves the question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; that capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to Latin America.
The liberal theory and the media claim, to get tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the governed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot interfere in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then wonder whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not today, according to its own selfish interests, lead politics and by the same way, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is a practically all-powerful and present lobby in all states.
It results in a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, by the provision of mutual benefits, in the legislation, where everything is condemned but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such, that due to the lack of funds, the national ministries delegate the drafting of laws to closely related lawyer offices.
The draft law was then adopted by the Bundestag.
The whole power does not come from the people, as the constitutions of the Western type declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is obvious that liberalism-oriented democracies are now rapidly faced with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled “The crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompeii”: “The state was long in full delicence and the functions were attributed by violence.
The pots-de-vin, the benefits obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The bottom-to-table and corruption spread unlimited and the people went to the elections with already sold voices..." ... "The honest people did not seek to obtain functions at all, it resulted once the state remained eight months without consuls" ... "We really began to say that the remedy for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man..." It is true that Appianos had in the mind Pompée, but it is Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolute regime.
In conclusion, as in ancient times, today’s society is based on the preference of personal profits, regardless of the interests of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and claim the interests of society as a whole.
It results, today as before, in an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the scrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the present state of things, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of break before a new stage.
The fact that today’s elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future human life losses, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The abolition of the law on public utility works is not a solution, at least in the long run.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at the international and domestic level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to decrease the social level of the population.
This trend is systematic.
The solution consists of sociopolitical reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase citizens’ influence on the government and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
