The film Argo: When everything goes worst, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist students attacked the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats as hostages.
They had to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The captured diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algeria government.
Their fate raised a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iran feeling in the United States.
The Iranian defeat contributed greatly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by actor and screenwriter Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a little victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees fled the embassy.
After complicated periods, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rocambolic cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a filming team that came to make signs for the filming of a great science fiction film.
Combination of gender
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores this film project, press conferences were held and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film was based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is part of a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - like, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres are successive: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were retranscribed in the film, there are no big differences),
light passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with dressed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected scenery and his acting game ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long-movie after the dark police "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It’s also Affleck’s first film that doesn’t take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates that sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran “is held” by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity that also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false filming team in the Tehran bazar).
Too much action in too many places
The screenwriter had to satisfy himself with a subject that in fact offers just a few exciting scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It goes out very well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the crisis threat at Tehran airport is removed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track are quite pulled by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipate character, due to the need to show too many events at too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role of Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a greater place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it leaves itself to be seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the performance and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet, in a certain way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the case.
