The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conduct a public investigation of the most absurd bank expenses every year, has now decided to launch the contest of regulations or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
“The fact that the EU is considering, in recent times, to adopt a quota of 40 percent of women for the management of major European companies has been the source of our decision,” said Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is, for example, already the recent decision of the European Court to unify the insurance prizes for men and women.
Until now, however, women were beneficial in terms of life insurance rates because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
“The vote will take place before the end of February 2013,” Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the obligation to add organic components to fuel, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition of using reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of the cages of chickens, which led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticisms have also been issued in the past against the prohibition of the use of the expression "butter" or the withdrawal from the sale of traditional lamps.
The quality of the bananas must have a size of 14 centimeters.
The European administration often reacts under the pressure of a commercial or industrial lobby whose requests are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (thus the Czech Republic currently imposes requests from its banks by threatening to use its veto right).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, the source of the fact that in the Union, bananas should not be of a size less than 14 cm or present an abnormal curb.
The European Commission defended itself by argumenting that it was only to harmonize non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
The standards for fruits and vegetables have been relieved despite the opposition of some states, claiming that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to the last year’s EU regulation that must contain on the swallowable ballons a warning indicating that children under 8 years should not swallow without adult surveillance.
The EU has referred to a U.S. investigation that ballons are, among the toys, the main cause of children’s deaths from drowning.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to breathing in fair trompets.
We also have some strange ideas.
The following rule concerning the European officials themselves is quite absurd: due to the sensitivity of this topic to Greece, any person having an official function within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonian" and must, instead, speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Let's Do" which group liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com named in this investigation, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU Regulation on the volume of food reserves on the territory of the Czech Republic.
