Here is my proposal for the Book Mountains of Spijkenisse, or, as we say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros came out of land.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes a ground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and citizens' houses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the Book Mountains received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
That is how this small town, which so far had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and a city of an upset wrath, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now possesses the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under the cheese clock.
Certainly, an elevator carries you to the heart of the massive, but the real joy of reading and architecture opens to you when you walk the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The whole glass interior is bright and clear, the Dutch roof floor and the elegant reverbers speak the language of the municipal public places.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking from the sight of public banks, dogs and little boys and little girls playing the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Willy Maas.
We completely disrupted the classic space configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the book mountain was carefully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the building’s technical center.
