“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Spijkenisse municipality, in a response to Standard.
This is how one day we found in a frisonne agricultural enterprise an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, a millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrat in greenhouses and fields.
It’s cheap and we save time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such amounts, in plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resilient material, whose smell refers to both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 stairs is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary cafe offers a stunning view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
