This is finally a new starting point for the birth of a identity.
Szabo: “The Germans must play a greater role.”
Germany voted on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision put Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request to obtain the status of observer state from the United Nations.
He then chose to abstain.
Why to?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious because it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the US position.
Germany wanted to declare its independence, but not to be too critical to Israel.
During the March 2011 Rebellion in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain when voting on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
At the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to get away from a policy so-called defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Furthermore, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are facing on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they’re still struggling to find this role, but they’re on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy, such as France or the UK
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national records.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by its exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other great powers: therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany’s position towards the conflict in the Middle East and the abstinence during the UN vote?
Germany first has significant outbreaks in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
Therefore, Berlin must be careful not to hit the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I’t give it too much importance, because it’s not a exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in the German strategic reflection.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by choosing abstinence in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans understand the position of Germany perfectly.
That’s why I think the fraction is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Maybe even Germany will be more respected.
In fact, Germany has demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are different.
The United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Are the opinions different between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the U.S. internal political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinions are not so large as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from filling with enthusiasm towards Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany experience difficulties in conciliating its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the great European partners, on the other hand?
This does not make it easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter into a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But I think the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that marks more their independence.
Does Germany see itself playing a role of weight actor on the international stage, does Germany just want to take on a key role?
Or is it always difficult to take on top roles?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is always uncomfortable to it and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties to play a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
This does not make it easier for the Germans.
In fact, it’s always the same problem: we don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to compone with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and that’s not easy.
