Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are brands known worldwide.
Armani Polo, what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but that has nothing to do with the original company.
The brand enjoys such a protection that the company that carries its name cannot complain.
And even if she could, it’s not sure she would get a cause gain.
“It’s increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing cabinet specializing in breach of property rights in the Far East.
Every week a new file comes to my office.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to be able to record their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports items.
Pattloch opens a booklet in which the records are recorded at the Beijing Brand Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company submitted the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by owning a part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
