“The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is huge.”
Financial losses and justice costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially when it comes to expensive high-end products.
According to the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of €15 billion, the world’s third-largest luxury product market and the fastest growing market.
However, it is not easy to delete the doubtful records from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports the trials during which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long period, the denomination criticized had become a “market reality.”
Pattloch explains that if the complainant has no luck, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, because he would have damaged his brand in China.
Sometimes this is the rule of the jungle.
Famous cases are also related to graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler had lost a legal battle against the construction machine maker Sany, the same company that just bought the beton pump maker Putzmeister.
That’s why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo acquirer, used before a blue and white logo that reminded the BMW. The conflict was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against the plagiars of Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
The Chinese authorities say they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing, however, admits that it had some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office would have passed last year from a “urgency situation in the course of the work to a normalized.”
So, the number of untreated opposition procedures would have decreased by 22%.
