However, 81,500 procedures are still suffering in the office.
Action is expensive
As often in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million registration applications, a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and this means that China is for the tenth consecutive time in the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal brands, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office had accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration rights.
In other words, each registration an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family company Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarism.
Of course, the Germans were able to obtain that the illegal manufacturing of vehicle components was suspended.
However, the imitators were able to maintain their Chinese rights on the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because family names cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, chairman of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The brand office therefore rejected the Munich’s objection.
Freudenberg has gained cause in the following two instances, but the opposite party continues to fight until today.
The vigilance is put on
The case is currently in court at the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome from the trial and praises the professionalism of judges.
However, he adds: "The procedure is long, challenging and it costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess the internal costs. The archive service has even had to review the acts of the last hundred years to provide evidence.
