For example, a Chinese manufacturer wanted to deposit in Germany the name of Freudenberg for a shoe and leather manufacturing company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: “The vigilance is put on.”
Pattloch and he advise German companies to be very cautious in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected," as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much greater than those of registration.
