Facts About Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Among the bacterial ISTs are syphilis, chlamydia and blennorragia (or gonorrhea).
Common ISTs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
The puppies of the pubis and the gall belong to the parasitic ISTs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorragia often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that male sexual intercourse causes at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidosis (phongic), blennorragy and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, the rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher than in other population groups.
According to European reports, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In Germany, human papillomavirus is common among young people.
What is the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
