Bradley Manning has not complained of bad treatment, the prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning had been a victim during the detention.
Manning was arrested in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping was done under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning — accused of being the source of the largest flight of confidential information in the history of the U.S. army — missed many occasions to complain of the misbehavior he allegedly suffered during his military detention.
During a counter-interrogation with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits rendered to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints regarding his treatment.
The counter-interrogation -- during a hearing, the defence submitted a request requiring that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping was done in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that officers had filled after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to a maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment that his guards reserved for him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had in prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints for ill-treatment, although officers have directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had verbally expressed concerns regarding certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and said they would take care of it, but they did not record the issues mentioned.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after dealing with the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
The military judge Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain of his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had gathered to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury."
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status — a level below close surveillance for suicide risk — for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I’m going well, and I wanted to be withdrawn from this status... to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for two months before being transferred to the military prison of the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he planned to commit suicide when he was in Kuwait and once disappeared due to the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not kept aware of what was going to happen to him or what was going to happen in the rest of the world was very angry.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent the clearest of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, a cover, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying during the day was contrary to the rule.
Manning also specified that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lighted outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned in the night, they woke him up so that he could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation in his Thursday testimony—that after being forced to sleep naked all a night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked before the guards and other prisoners one morning, during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time he was allowed to cover himself with a cover during the appeal.
During the question of the judge on Friday, Manning said he had deducted from the order of his guard that he had to release his cover that could have hidden his nakedness, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release her.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because he had tried to prove to a officer that he was not a danger for himself.
Manning had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his slip or tongs to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, his tongs, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will considerably reduce his sentence if he should be found guilty before a martial court, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
Defence said Manning intends to claim guilty of the less serious crimes and to fight for the abandonment of other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is expected to start again this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was imprisoned in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all prisoners in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of goods or public documents, the collusion with the enemy, giving rise to the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defence.
