After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets he charges on his shoulders through the sharp paths.
There are only 250 meters to the peak of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, to a turtle shade, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so that they don’t break down and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them life, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for every kilogram of sulfur extracted.
Once up, there is a road between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and wearing heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has installed a little down at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
