The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Declaration of Lima being made public, although it has been previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven members present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Unasur's Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency have initially that it will be disclosed after the closure of the summit, and then claimed that it will be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When interrogated on the text, they that its content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during short press statements.
The access of journalists to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachments of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd Summit of South America (ASPA) and, at this occasion, although this was instinctively requested by the press, it had not also broadcast the statement also called the Declaration of Lima, as it had been previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published in March last year.
During the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to establish secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited to the maximum access to information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that resolves a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the CIJ’s decision to hear the claims of both parties in the trial that Lima brought against Santiago and which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we bring today before this international court,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chili has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts,” President Piñera added, giving a hand to President Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the CIJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international court, after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua which it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of Brazilian presidents, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the UNASUR since 2011 after the resignation of its former president Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the talks in the morning and closing the summit shortly afternoon in Lima.
The mandate read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines of 31 projects had been fixed between the South American countries for a total of $17 million investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of the UNASUR will set up "important steps to the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits."
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to drugs, affordable internet access throughout South America, and to evaluate in a joint and effective way the risks of natural disasters."
With Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphal matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and see a better future for our populations,” President Humala concluded.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” Peruvian President said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give the wider details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that this country’s electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbors, is another topic discussed at the summit.
