Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is all my life"
The global basketball player "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the field and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of the local basketball as big as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain bleeding condemns him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes has been immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether it is as a player of lower leagues, player of the national basketball team, manager and manager of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros of Bayamón or as president of the basketball federation.
“I’ve been wearing several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was BSN’s chairman, national team’s general director and federation’s chairman during the 90s,” Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball is my whole life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind his out-of-standard route, witness this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those that remind him of his passage as a player within the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s to 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or team manager.
“These were my best years, those of which I’ve most profited because I’ve had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
This has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired at the championship in 1981, the year when Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great manager, took the head of the team," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been the leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, “I have a hard player for you, he measures two meters.
You want it?”
This is how to start Mincy, one of the best players that Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember that he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us to try to win another.
He rejoiced the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his tasks and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup where we reached 4th and where we would have had to win the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us replay the last match, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup the best national team you’ve ever seen?
She is one of the best, just as she defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favourite is that of the Pan-American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and we put a rack on the U.S. team, which was quite similar to that which had won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 due to a knee problem.
A team that was not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and a great joy at the pre-olympic tournament in Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner in replacement of the players suspended by the Mar del Plata Pan-American Games, we won the gold against all the forecasts.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
There is no doubt that it is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Piculín did.
And that without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best portorican leader?
It is very difficult to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
What is your biggest success in the Federation?
Having been part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have wanted to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, Ponce boys only play in their area and only face teams from the other corners of the island during national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for managers, field staff and arbitrators.
This makes me happy.
What do you do today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch videos of my time on YouTube, I enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, I watch basketball matches.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been next to me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas), became worldwide known by the main role of John Ross Ewing, more known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he incarnated a scrupulous, scary, and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the scrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the TV series "Dallas" has become a symbol of wealth in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday evening from complications of a cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back to his dear native town of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of her wife in the original and subsequent series, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said her adjunct, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and he will miss me a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life in depth," Gray said in a statement.
The doctors had diagnosed a liver cirrhosis to Larry Hagman in 1992 and had recognized that he had drunk a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and was transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of a ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In this, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a fascinating genius, played by Barbara Eden, and that he brought it home.
He also played in two comedies that remained shortly on the antenna, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among her roles in the film, there are roles well received by the critic in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his magical interpretation of the deliciously hateful J.R. that Larry Hagman experienced his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an emotion-filled episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculations around the world and millions of dollars played in betting.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series has reached a record of audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made Dallas the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was the sister of J.R., Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot her up.
J.R. had put her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she didn’t leave the city, but other people also had reasons to attack her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: an unrighteous entrepreneur and an unfaithful spouse who tried to intern his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
“I know what would be needed as a epitaffe for J.R,” Hagman said in 1988.
It should be written: “This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing.”
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, the coprotagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a "immensive man, both on the small screen and in life."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the luck to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already completed for the second season and a sixth is being performed, the channel.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT channel have announced how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
