The “End of the World” course has just begun.
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria and climate warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hameon there: the end of the "big count" of the Maya calendar, on 21 December, to which many people refer to as being the proof of the end of the world imminent.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what was waiting for him over the following months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a tax gap that some have called the "Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever experienced," Charmé said to his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what has happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he’s not the only teacher to give courses on “the end of the world” this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker displays the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas spread over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared to real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in the event that the world would not disappear,” said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exam.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which does not leave the students another choice than to work “up to the very night of the supposed end of the world,” Restall said.
The courses are quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his high-level student course, consisting of 35 students.
We received email messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, on their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether it is secular or religious, is just a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of Psychology and Nursing, says he has watched all the apocalyptic films.
“I’ve never heard of a class that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students questioned, and even less a professor, told us to believe in the end date of the world on December 21.
“Our first project was about the Maya prophecy, and in a certain way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old Temple student from West Chester.
The Mayas have never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I admit that there is an anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back to several centuries, which makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused an increase in these speculations.
“In other places in the world, people don’t think of it,” he assures.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who gives courses to the Philippines this year, quickly answered when asked if he knew that there were courses about "the end of the world."
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it was an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, we have talked about the many presumed dates of the last judgment, and he affirms that if nothing happens on December 21, "People will immediately begin to think about the next date" or to philosophy on the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date to light.
Many told us that they thought to go to holidays "from the end of the world".
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communication student.
